# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: phenylalanine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:phenylalanine/1-3-dimethylbutylamine] The hydrochloride and citrate salts of DMBA has been identified as unapproved ingredients in some over-the-counter dietary supplements, in which it is used in an apparent attempt to circumvent bans on methylhexanamine.
[src:phenylalanine/1-3-dimethylbutylamine] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) considers any dietary supplement containing DMBA to be "adulterated".
[src:phenylalanine/1-3-dimethylbutylamine] Despite the FDA's opposition, DMBA continues to be sold in the US.
[src:phenylalanine/1-3-dimethylbutylamine] There are no known human safety studies on DMBA and its health effects are entirely unknown.
[src:phenylalanine/1-3-dimethylbutylamine] DMBA is not an agonist of the rodent or human trace amine-associated receptor 1 (TAAR1).
[src:phenylalanine/1-3-dimethylbutylamine] The substance is listed in doping group S6B, by WADA.
[src:phenylalanine/1-3-dimethylbutylamine] One Norwegian football player has tested above the limit.
[src:phenylalanine/1-3-dimethylbutylamine] However, in 2026 media told about investigation and conclusion that indicates that the substance came from the court that this player (and her team) played upon.
[src:phenylalanine/1-4-dimethylamylamine] 1,4-DMAA has been identified in dietary supplements.
[src:phenylalanine/1-4-dimethylamylamine] It produces sympathomimetic effects in animals and humans.
[src:phenylalanine/1-4-dimethylamylamine] 1,4-DMAA and other alkylamine stimulants may act as catecholamine releasing agents.
[src:phenylalanine/1-4-dimethylamylamine] Unlike octodrine and methylhexanamine, 1,4-DMAA has never been used as a pharmaceutical drug.
[src:phenylalanine/1-fluoro-18f-1-deoxyephedrine] It has high lipophilicity, allowing it to penetrate the blood-brain barrier without hindrance, which was accompanied by high, uniform uptake by the brain (approximately 8% of the administered dose), similar to that observed for the structurally related analogue [11C]methamphetamine.
[src:phenylalanine/1-fluoro-18f-1-deoxyephedrine] The ephedrine (1R,2S) isomer is three times more effective than the pseudoephedrine (1S,2S) isomer, it is a metabolically stable compound.
[src:phenylalanine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] The stereoisomer (*S*)-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (also referred to as L-P5C) is an intermediate metabolite in the biosynthesis and degradation of proline and arginine.
[src:phenylalanine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In prokaryotic proline biosynthesis, GSA is synthesized from γ-glutamyl phosphate by the enzyme γ-glutamyl phosphate reductase.
[src:phenylalanine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In most eukaryotes, GSA is synthesised from the amino acid glutamate by the bifunctional enzyme 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate synthase (P5CS).
[src:phenylalanine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] The human P5CS is encoded by the *ALDH18A1* gene.
[src:phenylalanine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] The enzyme pyrroline-5-carboxylate reductase converts L-P5C into proline.
[src:phenylalanine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In proline degradation, the enzyme proline dehydrogenase produces P5C from proline, and the enzyme 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate dehydrogenase converts GSA to glutamate.
[src:phenylalanine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In many prokaryotes, proline dehydrogenase and P5C dehydrogenase form a bifunctional enzyme that prevents the release of P5C during proline degradation.
[src:phenylalanine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] A reciprocal regulation of delta 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate synthetase (P5CS) and proline dehydrogenase genes controls proline levels during and after osmotic stress in plants proportional to the level of proline.
[src:phenylalanine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] This allows an optimum level of proline to be produced from reduced nitrogen to control osmotic stress.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] Bupropion is substantially converted into metabolites during first-pass metabolism with oral administration and levels of its metabolites are much higher than those of bupropion itself.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] Exposure to (2*R*,3*R*)-hydroxybupropion is 29-fold higher than to (*R*)-bupropion and exposure to (2*S*,3*S*)-hydroxybupropion is 3.7-fold higher than to (*S*)-bupropion.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] Other metabolites that circulate at higher concentrations than those of bupropion include threohydrobupropion and to a lesser extent erythrohydrobupropion.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] The metabolism of bupropion and its metabolites is stereoselective.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] During bupropion therapy, exposure to (*R*)-bupropion is 2- to 6-fold higher than to (*S*)-bupropion and exposure to (2*R*,3*R*)-hydroxybupropion is 20- to 65-fold higher than to (2*S*,3*S*)-hydroxybupropion.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] Hence, (2*R*,3*R*)-hydroxybupropion is a major metabolite of bupropion and (2*S*,3*S*)-hydroxybupropion is a minor metabolite.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] In contrast to humans, only low levels of hydroxybupropion or (2*R*,3*R*)-hydroxybupropion occur with bupropion in rats.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] This highlights substantial species differences in the pharmacokinetics of bupropion between animals and humans.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] These differences in turn may account for differences in the pharmacodynamic effects of bupropion between species.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] (2*R*,3*R*)-Hydroxybupropion is much less pharmacologically active as a monoamine reuptake inhibitor than bupropion or (2*S*,3*S*)-hydroxybupropion.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] Conversely, its potency as a negative allosteric modulator of nicotinic acetylcholine receptors is variable but overall more similar to that of bupropion and (2*S*,3*S*)-hydroxybupropion.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] The smaller the value, the more avidly the compound affects the site.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] Additional studies have characterized the affinities (Ki) of bupropion and the hydroxybupropion enantiomers at the monoamine transporters as well as affinities and potencies (IC50) using non-human proteins.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] In contrast to bupropion and (2*S*,3*S*)-hydroxybupropion, racemic hydroxybupropion, using rat proteins, has been found to act as a selective norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor (IC50 = 1,700 nM) with no apparent inhibition of dopamine reuptake (IC50 > 10,000 nM).
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] Normally, activity with racemic mixtures is expected to be closer to that of the active enantiomer than to the inactive enantiomer.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] The reasons for the discrepancy in the case of racemic hydroxybupropion are unclear.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] In any case, it was suggested that (2*R*,3*R*)-hydroxybupropion might be acting as a negative allosteric modulator of the binding of (2*S*,3*S*)-hydroxybupropion to the dopamine transporter.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] Bupropion and (2*S*,3*S*)-hydroxybupropion are substantially more potent than (2*R*,3*R*)-hydroxybupropion in various rodent behavioral tests, such as the forced swim test (an assay of antidepressant-like activity).
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] However, sufficient doses of bupropion, (2*S*,3*S*)-hydroxybupropion, and (2*R*,3*R*)-hydroxybupropion all produce full methamphetamine-like effects in monkeys (1 mg/kg, 3 mg/kg, and 10 mg/kg, respectively).
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] Bupropion produces nicotine-like effects in rodents and (2*S*,3*S*)-hydroxybupropion partially substitutes for nicotine.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] In contrast, (2*R*,3*R*)-hydroxybupropion does not substitute for nicotine and dose-dependently antagonizes the effects of nicotine by up to 50%.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] (2*R*,3*R*)-Hydroxybupropion is a strong CYP2D6 inhibitor similarly to bupropion.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] (2*R*,3*R*)-Hydroxybupropion alone has been estimated to account for approximately 65% of the total *in vivo* CYP2D6 inhibition of bupropion, whereas threohydrobupropion accounted for 21% and erythrohydrobupropion accounted for 9% (with 5% remaining or unaccounted for).
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] Hydroxybupropion, including both (2*R*,3*R*)-hydroxybupropion and (2*S*,3*S*)-hydroxybupropion, is mainly formed from bupropion by the cytochrome P450 enzyme CYP2B6.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] However, CYP2C19, CYP3A4, CYP1A2, and CYP2E1 appear to play a minor role.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] CYP2B6 is highly polymorphic and is subject to high interindividual variability of approximately 100-fold.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] This may result in large interindividual differences in the metabolism of bupropion into hydroxybupropion and the effects of bupropion.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] However, clearance of bupropion is not affected in different CYP2B6 metabolizer phenotypes.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] This suggests that other enzymes compensate in the metabolism of bupropion in the context of reduced CYP2B6 function.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] The moderate CYP2B6 inducer rifampicin increased the clearance of (2*R*,3*R*)-hydroxybupropion and decreased its exposure and half-life by approximately 50%.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] The elimination half-life of (2*R*,3*R*)-hydroxybupropion is 19 to 26 hours.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] Hydroxybupropion has two chiral centers.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] As a result, there are four possible enantiomers of the compound.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] However, only (2*R*,3*R*)-hydroxybupropion and (2*S*,3*S*)-hydroxybupropion are formed in humans.
[src:phenylalanine/2r-3r-hydroxybupropion] (2*R*,3*S*)- and (2*S*,3*R*)-Hydroxybupropion do not occur in humans presumably due to steric hindrance precluding their formation.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] It can be viewed as a benzyl group substituted for the methyl group of alanine, or a phenyl group in place of a terminal hydrogen of alanine.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] It is classified as neutral, and nonpolar because of the inert and hydrophobic nature of the benzyl side chain.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] The L-isomer is used to biochemically form proteins coded for by DNA.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] Phenylalanine is a precursor for tyrosine, the monoamine neurotransmitters dopamine, norepinephrine (noradrenaline), and epinephrine (adrenaline), and the biological pigment melanin.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] It is encoded by the messenger RNA codons UUU and UUC.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] The one-letter symbol F was assigned to phenylalanine for its phonetic similarity.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] The first description of phenylalanine was made in 1879, when Schulze and Barbieri identified a compound with the empirical formula, C9H11NO2, in yellow lupine (*Lupinus luteus*) seedlings.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] In 1882, Erlenmeyer and Lipp first synthesized phenylalanine from phenylacetaldehyde, hydrogen cyanide, and ammonia.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] The genetic codon for phenylalanine was first discovered by J.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] They showed that by using mRNA to insert multiple uracil repeats into the genome of the bacterium *E. coli*, they could cause the bacterium to produce a polypeptide consisting solely of repeated phenylalanine amino acids.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] This discovery helped to establish the nature of the coding relationship that links information stored in genomic nucleic acid with protein expression in the living cell.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] Good sources of phenylalanine are eggs, chicken, liver, beef, milk, and soybeans.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] Another common source of phenylalanine is anything sweetened with the artificial sweetener aspartame, such as diet drinks, diet foods and medication; the metabolism of aspartame produces phenylalanine as one of the compound's metabolites.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] The Food and Nutrition Board (FNB) of the U.S.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] Institute of Medicine set Recommended Dietary Allowances (RDAs) for essential amino acids in 2002.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] For phenylalanine plus tyrosine, for adults 19 years and older, 33 mg/kg body weight/day.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] In 2005, the DRI was set to 27 mg/kg per day (with no tyrosine), the FAO/WHO/UNU recommendation of 2007 is 25 mg/kg per day (with no tyrosine).
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] As an essential amino acid, phenylalanine is not synthesized by animals, which must obtain it from dietary sources such as meat, dairy, eggs, and legumes.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] Bacteria, archaea, fungi, algae, some protozoans and plants biosynthesize phenylalanine via the shikimate pathway.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] While animals cannot synthesize phenylalanine, they can break it down.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] Through an irreversible reaction, the liver enzyme phenylalanine hydroxylase (PAH) converts phenylalanine into tyrosine.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] L-Phenylalanine is biologically converted into L-tyrosine, another one of the DNA-encoded amino acids.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] L-tyrosine in turn is converted into L-DOPA, which is further converted into dopamine, norepinephrine (noradrenaline), and epinephrine (adrenaline).
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] The latter three are known as the catecholamines.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] Phenylalanine uses the same active transport channel as tryptophan to cross the blood–brain barrier.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] In excessive quantities, supplementation can interfere with the production of serotonin and other aromatic amino acids as well as nitric oxide due to the overuse (eventually, limited availability) of the associated cofactors, iron or tetrahydrobiopterin.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] The corresponding enzymes for those compounds are the aromatic amino acid hydroxylase family and nitric oxide synthase.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] Phenylalanine is the starting compound used in the synthesis of flavonoids.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] Lignan is derived from phenylalanine and from tyrosine.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] Phenylalanine is converted to cinnamic acid by the enzyme phenylalanine ammonia-lyase.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] The genetic disorder phenylketonuria (PKU) is the inability to metabolize phenylalanine because of a lack of the enzyme phenylalanine hydroxylase.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] Individuals with this disorder are known as "phenylketonurics" and must regulate their intake of phenylalanine.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] Phenylketonurics often use blood tests to monitor the amount of phenylalanine in their blood.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] Lab results may report phenylalanine levels using either mg/dL and μmol/L.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] One mg/dL of phenylalanine is approximately equivalent to 60 μmol/L.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] A (rare) "variant form" of phenylketonuria called hyperphenylalaninemia is caused by the inability to synthesize a cofactor called tetrahydrobiopterin, which can be supplemented.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] Pregnant women with hyperphenylalaninemia may show similar symptoms of the disorder (high levels of phenylalanine in blood), but these indicators will usually disappear at the end of gestation.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] Pregnant women with PKU must control their blood phenylalanine levels even if the fetus is heterozygous for the defective gene because the fetus could be adversely affected due to hepatic immaturity.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] A non-food source of phenylalanine is the artificial sweetener aspartame.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] This compound is metabolized by the body into several chemical byproducts including phenylalanine.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] The breakdown problems phenylketonurics have with the buildup of phenylalanine in the body also occurs with the ingestion of aspartame, although to a lesser degree.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] These warnings are placed to help individuals avoid such foods.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] The stereoisomer D-phenylalanine (DPA) can be produced by conventional organic synthesis, either as a single enantiomer or as a component of the racemic mixture.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] It does not participate in protein biosynthesis although it is found in proteins in small amounts—particularly aged proteins and food proteins that have been processed.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] The biological functions of D-amino acids remain unclear, although D-phenylalanine has pharmacological activity at niacin receptor 2.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] DL-Phenylalanine (DLPA) is marketed as a nutritional supplement for its purported analgesic and antidepressant activities, which have been supported by clinical trials.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] DL-Phenylalanine is a mixture of D-phenylalanine and L-phenylalanine.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] The reputed analgesic activity of DL-phenylalanine may be explained by the possible blockage by D-phenylalanine of enkephalin degradation by the enzyme carboxypeptidase A.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] Enkephalins act as agonists of the mu and delta opioid receptors, and agonists of these receptors are known to produce antidepressant effects.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] Elevated brain levels of norepinephrine and dopamine are thought to have an antidepressant effect.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] D-Phenylalanine is absorbed from the small intestine and transported to the liver via the portal circulation.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] A small amount of D-phenylalanine appears to be converted to L-phenylalanine.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] D-Phenylalanine is distributed to the various tissues of the body via the systemic circulation.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] It appears to cross the blood–brain barrier less efficiently than L-phenylalanine, and so a small amount of an ingested dose of D-phenylalanine is excreted in the urine without penetrating the central nervous system.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] L-Phenylalanine is an antagonist at α2δ Ca2+ calcium channels with a Ki of 980 nM.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] In the brain, L-phenylalanine is a competitive antagonist at the glycine binding site of NMDA receptor and at the glutamate binding site of AMPA receptor.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] L-Phenylalanine is produced for medical, feed, and nutritional applications, such as aspartame, in large quantities by utilizing the bacterium *Escherichia coli*, which naturally produces aromatic amino acids like phenylalanine.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] The quantity of L-phenylalanine produced commercially has been increased by genetically engineering *E. coli*, such as by altering the regulatory promoters or amplifying the number of genes controlling enzymes responsible for the synthesis of the amino acid.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] Borofalan (boronophenylalanine) is a dihydroxyboryl derivative of phenylalanine, used in neutron capture therapy.
[src:phenylalanine/phenylalanine] 4-Azido-L-phenylalanine is a protein-incorporated unnatural amino acid used as a tool for bioconjugation in the field of chemical biology.
